Project - Predicting Potential Credit Card Payment Defaulters¶

FEATURIZATION, MODEL SELECTION & TUNING¶

The purpose of this project is to build classification model and apply feature engineering methods to good accuracy ensuring less prediction errors for estimating credit card defaulters in the coming month.The model predicts whether a late-paying customer will only be late or if this customer is predicted not to make a payment at all. This makes it a classification problem.The following are the attributes of the dataset Limit : Customer Credit Limit Gender : Customer Gender (1 = male, 2 = female) Education : Customer Education level (1 = Graduate school, 2 = University, 3 = High school, 4 = Others) Marriage : Customer Marriage Status (1 = married, 2 = single, 3 = others) Age : Customer Age SEP_PYMT_STS : Credit Bill Payment Status in September (-1 = pay duly, x = payment delay for x month) AUG_PYMT_STS : Credit Bill Payment Status in August (-1 = pay duly, x = payment delay for x month) JUL_PYMT_STS : Credit Bill Payment Status in July (-1 = pay duly, x = payment delay for x month) JUN_PYMT_STS : Credit Bill Payment Status in June (-1 = pay duly, x = payment delay for x month) MAY_PYMT_STS : Credit Bill Payment Status in May (-1 = pay duly, x = payment delay for x month) APR_PYMT_STS : Credit Bill Payment Status in April (-1 = pay duly, x = payment delay for x month) SEP_STMT : Credit Bill Statement in September AUG_STMT : Credit Bill Statement in August JUL_STMT : Credit Bill Statement in July JUN_STMT : Credit Bill Statement in June MAY_STMT : Credit Bill Statement in May APR_STMT : Credit Bill Statement in April SEP_PAID : Amout Paid in September AUG_PAID : Amout Paid in August JUL_PAID : Amout Paid in July JUN_PAID : Amout Paid in June MAY_PAID : Amout Paid in May APR_PAID : Amout Paid in April Default : Will Default Next Month

def doPlots(x, data, ii, fun):   
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(len(ii) // 2, ncols = 2)
    fig.tight_layout()
    for i in range(len(ii)):
        fun(x=x[ii[i]], data=data, ax=axes[i // 2, i % 2], color='Blue')
    plt.show()

Descriptive statistics is meant to know how data is distributed.What does descriptive statistics indicates 1. If mean not equal to Median(Q2) indicates the existance of tail. If mean > median, long tail on right side. Skew on right side. If mean < median, long tail on left side. Skew on left side 2. When we observe difference between (Q1,min) and (Q3,max) is not same data is not symmetric meaning If difference between (Q1,min) > (Q3,max) indicates existance of long skewed tail on left side If difference between (Q1,min) < (Q3,max) indicates existance of long skewed tail on right side 3. When we have longs skews, indicates existance of ourliers. Based on the understanding what we can infer from the above is Section A --------- 1. The first column represents count, which is number of records. In this case all features have no missing values 2. The second column mean value (average) of each column 3. The third column std value (standard deviation) of each column 4. The fourth column mean value (average) of each column 5. The fifth column min value (minimum) of each column 6. The sixth column 25% value (Q1-quartile) of each column 7. The sixth column 50% value (Q2-quartile) of each column. Also known as Median 8. The sixth column 75% value (Q3-quartile) of each column 9. The sixth column max value (maximum) of each column Summary ------- No Missing values No Outliers

Apply multiple classification models to extract the Important features¶

In [90]:
Model     = []
Accuracy  = [] 
AUC       = [] 

def show_features(db,coeff,Score,roc,heading):
    
    Score        = Score *100
    Coefficients = pd.DataFrame(coeff)    
   
    if (heading == "Logistic Regression"):
        Coefficients         = np.transpose(Coefficients)

    Coefficients.columns = ['Coefficients']
    Features = pd.DataFrame(list(db.iloc[:,:-1]))
    Features.columns = ['Features']
    Features = pd.concat([Features,Coefficients,],axis=1) 
    print(Features)
    print(" ")
    print("Accuracy : %.2f" % Score)
    print('AUC      : %.2f' % roc)
    
    
    f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5))
    sns.barplot(x=Features["Features"],y= Features["Coefficients"],palette="prism",linewidth=1,edgecolor="Black",ax=ax)
    sns.set_context('talk') 
    ax.tick_params(axis='x', colors='black')
    ax.tick_params(axis='y', colors='blue')
    header = "Feature Importance by " + heading
    plt.title(header,fontsize = 14,weight = 'bold')
    plt.xlabel('Features', fontsize = 15, weight = 'bold')
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.ylabel('Coefficients', fontsize = 15, weight = 'bold')
    plt.grid(False)
    plt.show()
                  
    Model.append(heading)
    Accuracy.append(Score)
    AUC.append(roc)
         
    return

Model_     = []
Accuracy_  = [] 
AUC_       = []

def Get_Metrics(Score,roc,heading):
                 
    Score  = Score *100
    Model_.append(heading)
    Accuracy_.append(Score)
    AUC_.append(roc)
        
    print(heading)
    print("Accuracy : %.2f" % Score)
    print('AUC      : %.2f' % roc)
    return

Ada Boost Classifier - Hyper Parameter Tuning¶

The boosting algorithm Adaboost (when using a tree) has three core parameters: - number of weak learners to train - learning rate - max nb of splits (depth of tree)

Gradient Boosting Classifier - Hyper Parameter Tuning¶

min_samples_split = 500 : This should be ~0.5-1% of total values. Since this is imbalanced class problem, well take a small value from the range. min_samples_leaf = 50 : Can be selected based on intuition. This is just used for preventing overfitting and again a small value because of imbalanced classes. max_depth = 8 : Should be chosen (5-8) based on the number of observations and predictors. This has 87K rows and 49 columns so lets take 8 here. max_features = sqrt : Its a general thumb-rule to start with square root. subsample = 0.8 : This is a commonly a start value
In [114]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

              'n_estimators': [500],
